WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Woman: And now one of the most
respected investors in America

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:22.920
is going to tell you
about his secrets.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:32.960
Man: "Warren Buffett."
It's the sound of money.

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:35.620
$9.2 billion...
Woman 2: Billionaire investor Warren Buffett,

00:00:35.825 --> 00:00:37.258
the second richest man
in America.

00:00:37.458 --> 00:00:40.166
Man 2:
He's estimated to be worth about $62 billion.

00:00:40.366 --> 00:00:42.208
That makes him
the richest man in the world.

00:00:42.408 --> 00:00:44.917
????

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:50.542
Woman 3: You know,
Buffett is not exactly what you might expect.

00:00:50.742 --> 00:00:52.771
Woman 4:
Even though he's in the money business,

00:00:52.971 --> 00:00:55.000
he doesn't even own
a calculator or a computer.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:56.425
Man 3:
He takes the long view,

00:00:56.625 --> 00:01:00.291
and it's made him billions,
many billions.

00:01:02.125 --> 00:01:03.300
Man 4:
Maybe you can beat the house,

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:06.217
but I don't think you can beat
Warren Buffett.

00:01:06.417 --> 00:01:09.333
Man 5: Buffett filed his first
tax return at 13 years old.

00:01:09.533 --> 00:01:11.041
But he's no average
billionaire, Tom.

00:01:11.241 --> 00:01:12.550
Tom:
No, he certainly isn't, Matt.

00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:16.458
Woman 5:
He's a $44 billion average Joe.

00:01:18.333 --> 00:01:19.717
Man 7:
Warren Buffett has an approach

00:01:19.917 --> 00:01:23.333
that doesn't make him very popular
with his fellow billionaires.

00:01:25.166 --> 00:01:27.274
Man 8: Warren Buffett,
the boy from Nebraska

00:01:27.474 --> 00:01:29.383
who grew up to become
the Wizard of Omaha.

00:01:29.583 --> 00:01:31.625
Man 9: What was it about him
that allowed him to become

00:01:31.825 --> 00:01:33.834
the richest man in the world?
How did he do it?

00:01:34.034 --> 00:01:37.125
????

00:01:47.333 --> 00:01:50.883
Warren: 70 years ago,
I was in high school.

00:01:51.083 --> 00:01:54.333
Almost a third as long
as the country has been around.

00:01:55.417 --> 00:01:56.841
And when I was
in high school,

00:01:57.041 --> 00:01:59.208
I really only had
two things on my mind...

00:02:00.041 --> 00:02:01.508
girls and cars.

00:02:01.708 --> 00:02:04.500
And...
and I wasn't doing very well with girls,

00:02:04.700 --> 00:02:05.342
so we'll talk
about cars.

00:02:05.542 --> 00:02:09.383
But lets just imagine
that when we finish,

00:02:09.583 --> 00:02:14.792
I'm going to let each one of you
pick out the car of your choice.

00:02:14.992 --> 00:02:16.759
Sounds good, doesn't it?

00:02:16.959 --> 00:02:19.634
Pick it out,
any color, you name it,

00:02:19.834 --> 00:02:23.708
it'll be tied up with a bow,
and it'll be at your house tomorrow.

00:02:24.875 --> 00:02:27.875
And you say,
"Well, what's the catch?"

00:02:29.208 --> 00:02:30.592
And the catch is...

00:02:30.792 --> 00:02:34.483
that it's the only car you're
going to get in your lifetime.

00:02:34.683 --> 00:02:38.375
Now what are you going to do,
knowing that that's the only car

00:02:38.575 --> 00:02:40.592
you're ever going to have
and you love that car?

00:02:40.792 --> 00:02:44.208
You're going to take care of
it like you cannot believe.

00:02:44.959 --> 00:02:46.550
Now what I'd like to suggest

00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:49.583
is that you're not going to get
only one car in your lifetime,

00:02:49.783 --> 00:02:52.917
but you're gonna get
one body and one mind,

00:02:53.117 --> 00:02:54.508
and that's all
you're going to get.

00:02:54.708 --> 00:02:58.792
And that body and mind
feels terrific now,

00:02:58.992 --> 00:03:00.750
but it has
to last you a lifetime.

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:06.462
I'm on the way
to the office.

00:03:06.662 --> 00:03:08.375
It's all
of a five-minute drive.

00:03:09.417 --> 00:03:10.750
Been doing it...

00:03:11.792 --> 00:03:15.342
for 54 years.

00:03:15.542 --> 00:03:18.175
One of the good things
about this five-minute drive

00:03:18.375 --> 00:03:23.792
is that on the way there's a McDonald's,
so I'll pick up something.

00:03:26.291 --> 00:03:28.583
Woman on speaker: Good morning,
thank you for choosing McDonald's.

00:03:28.783 --> 00:03:29.800
Go ahead and order
whenever you're ready.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.333
I'll have a Sausage McMuffin
with egg and cheese.

00:03:34.533 --> 00:03:35.759
Woman: Anything else?
That's it, thank you.

00:03:35.959 --> 00:03:40.708
Warren: Yeah,
and I tell my wife as I shave in the morning,

00:03:40.908 --> 00:03:45.217
I say either $2.61,
$2.95, or $3.17,

00:03:45.417 --> 00:03:48.921
and she puts that amount
in a little cup by me here

00:03:49.121 --> 00:03:52.625
and that determines
which of three breakfasts I get.

00:03:52.825 --> 00:03:55.258
Hi. 2.95.
Okay, 2.95.

00:03:55.458 --> 00:03:57.337
There's the two.
How you doing, sir!

00:03:57.537 --> 00:03:59.648
Hey, great!
You're on "Candid Camera"!

00:03:59.848 --> 00:04:01.759
I see. Hello, everybody!

00:04:01.959 --> 00:04:04.546
Warren:
When I'm not feeling quite so prosperous,

00:04:04.746 --> 00:04:07.856
I might go with a 2.61,
which is two sausage patties,

00:04:08.056 --> 00:04:11.166
and then I put 'em together
and pour myself a Coke.

00:04:13.125 --> 00:04:16.300
Hi, how are you?
Hi. I've been good.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:20.250
3.17 is a bacon, egg,
and cheese biscuit,

00:04:20.450 --> 00:04:22.550
but the market's
down this morning,

00:04:22.750 --> 00:04:27.125
so I think I'll pass up the
3.17 and go with the 2.95.

00:04:27.325 --> 00:04:29.792
????

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.966
Warren:
I like numbers.

00:04:36.166 --> 00:04:38.917
It started before
I could remember.

00:04:41.333 --> 00:04:43.792
It just felt good,
working with numbers.

00:04:46.041 --> 00:04:48.708
I was always playing around with
numbers in one-way or another.

00:04:48.908 --> 00:04:50.800
And it was fun to have
a bunch of guys over

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.667
and have them betting on which
marble would reach the drain first.

00:04:56.667 --> 00:04:58.175
I had a lot
of energy as a kid.

00:04:58.375 --> 00:05:01.792
I... I was inquisitive,
and I was the youngest one

00:05:01.992 --> 00:05:03.583
always in the class,
'cause I'd skip.

00:05:03.783 --> 00:05:06.208
I've always been competitive.

00:05:08.708 --> 00:05:10.875
I liked to read
more than most kids.

00:05:11.075 --> 00:05:13.467
I really like
to read a lot.

00:05:13.667 --> 00:05:16.542
My Aunt Edie gave me
a copy of "The World Almanac"

00:05:16.742 --> 00:05:18.008
and that was heaven to me.

00:05:18.208 --> 00:05:24.041
And I can still tell you that Omaha's
population was 214,006 in 1930.

00:05:24.241 --> 00:05:26.467
Some numbers
just kind of stick with you.

00:05:26.667 --> 00:05:30.041
And very early,
probably when I was seven or so,

00:05:30.241 --> 00:05:32.374
I took this book out
of the Benson Library

00:05:32.574 --> 00:05:34.708
called "A Thousand Ways
to Make a $1,000."

00:05:36.667 --> 00:05:39.087
And one of the ways
in this book

00:05:39.287 --> 00:05:41.708
was having
penny weighing machines.

00:05:44.083 --> 00:05:47.166
And I sat and calculated
how much it would cost

00:05:47.366 --> 00:05:48.258
to buy the first
weighing machine,

00:05:48.258 --> 00:05:49.440
and then how long
it would take for the profit

00:05:49.759 --> 00:05:52.000
from that one to buy another one,
and I would sit there

00:05:52.617 --> 00:05:54.217
and create these
compound interest tables

00:05:54.417 --> 00:05:56.088
to figure out how long
it would take me to have

00:05:56.288 --> 00:05:57.959
a weighing machine
for every person in the world.

00:05:59.625 --> 00:06:02.467
I had everybody in the country
weighing themselves ten times a day,

00:06:02.667 --> 00:06:05.917
and me just sitting there like John
D. Rockefeller of weighing machines.

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:11.717
The allowance when I was a
little boy was a nickel a week,

00:06:11.917 --> 00:06:17.583
but I liked the idea of having a little
more than a nickel a week to work with,

00:06:17.783 --> 00:06:19.625
and I went
into business very early.

00:06:20.959 --> 00:06:23.500
I started selling Coca-Cola
door to door.

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:24.592
I sold gum door to door.

00:06:24.792 --> 00:06:25.966
I sold
"Saturday Evening Post,"

00:06:26.166 --> 00:06:28.542
"Liberty" magazine,
"Ladies Home Journal," you name it.

00:06:30.792 --> 00:06:33.583
I think I enjoyed the game
almost right from the start.

00:06:35.542 --> 00:06:38.258
But I like being my own boss.

00:06:38.458 --> 00:06:40.583
That's one thing I liked
about delivering papers.

00:06:41.792 --> 00:06:43.091
I could arrange
the route I wanted.

00:06:43.291 --> 00:06:46.458
Nobody was bothering me
at 5:00 or 6:00 in the morning.

00:06:50.458 --> 00:06:52.759
I was delivering
500 papers a day,

00:06:52.959 --> 00:06:56.208
and I made a penny a paper,
but in terms of compounding,

00:06:56.408 --> 00:06:58.583
that penny's turned
into something else.

00:06:58.783 --> 00:07:02.792
????

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.650
Einstein is reputed to have said
that "Compound interest

00:07:09.850 --> 00:07:11.800
is the eighth wonder of the world"
or something like that,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.417
and it goes back to that story you probably
learned when you were in grade school

00:07:16.617 --> 00:07:18.375
where somebody did
something for the king,

00:07:18.575 --> 00:07:20.770
and the king said,
"What can I do for you?"

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:22.966
And he said,
"Well, lets take a chessboard

00:07:23.166 --> 00:07:26.166
"and put one kernel of wheat
on the first square

00:07:26.366 --> 00:07:27.917
"and then double it
on the second

00:07:28.117 --> 00:07:29.425
and double it on the third."

00:07:29.625 --> 00:07:32.375
And the king readily agreed to it,
and by the time he figured out

00:07:32.575 --> 00:07:35.425
what two to the 64th
amounted to,

00:07:35.625 --> 00:07:37.508
he was giving away
the entire kingdom.

00:07:37.708 --> 00:07:42.133
So it's a pretty simple concept,
but over time,

00:07:42.333 --> 00:07:45.208
it accomplishes
extraordinary things.

00:07:51.041 --> 00:07:52.925
Berkshire is an amazing company.

00:07:53.125 --> 00:07:56.467
Fourth largest company
in the "Fortune" 500.

00:07:56.667 --> 00:08:00.508
He is the only person
who has ever, from scratch,

00:08:00.708 --> 00:08:05.500
built a company that is in the
top 10 of the Fortune 500.

00:08:10.875 --> 00:08:13.425
Woman: Berkshire Hathaway.
Fine, thank you.

00:08:13.625 --> 00:08:16.375
Warren: Well,
Berkshire is a holding company of sorts.

00:08:16.575 --> 00:08:20.417
It owns a large number
of separate businesses

00:08:20.617 --> 00:08:22.717
that operate
independently of each other

00:08:22.917 --> 00:08:27.083
and, to a great extent,
from the parent company, Berkshire Hathaway.

00:08:32.041 --> 00:08:34.208
All right, well,
we're going to get more from you in a second.

00:08:34.408 --> 00:08:37.166
Warren: So we have maybe 70,
maybe 80 businesses,

00:08:37.366 --> 00:08:39.749
and we ask them
to behave in a way

00:08:39.949 --> 00:08:42.133
that doesn't hurt
our reputation

00:08:42.333 --> 00:08:44.875
at Berkshire Hathaway,
but they run their own lives.

00:08:47.542 --> 00:08:51.375
Other people do most of the decorating in
the office, so various things come in.

00:08:53.041 --> 00:08:56.708
Originally,
when I moved in in 1962...

00:08:57.792 --> 00:08:58.925
you can see this...

00:08:59.125 --> 00:09:01.841
I went down
to the South Omaha Library,

00:09:02.041 --> 00:09:06.083
and I think for a dollar,
I got seven copies

00:09:06.283 --> 00:09:08.634
of old "New York Times"

00:09:08.834 --> 00:09:12.792
from big times like
the Panic of 1907.

00:09:12.992 --> 00:09:15.416
This is one...
1929 obviously.

00:09:15.616 --> 00:09:17.841
But I wanted
to put on the walls

00:09:18.041 --> 00:09:20.592
days of extreme panic
in Wall Street,

00:09:20.792 --> 00:09:24.583
just as a reminder that anything
can happen in this world.

00:09:24.783 --> 00:09:25.283
I mean it...

00:09:25.458 --> 00:09:27.792
it's instructive art
you can call it.

