00:09:36.417 --> 00:09:39.667
I was born in 1930
here in Omaha, Nebraska,

00:09:39.867 --> 00:09:41.000
during the stock market crash.

00:09:43.875 --> 00:09:48.500
My dad lost his job in 1931,
a year after I was born.

00:09:50.333 --> 00:09:51.550
He was a stock salesman,

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:54.291
and he had what little savings
he had in the bank,

00:09:54.491 --> 00:09:56.217
and so he started
his own company.

00:09:56.417 --> 00:09:58.166
He worked right through
the depression.

00:09:58.366 --> 00:10:00.291
????

00:10:02.959 --> 00:10:05.834
Bertie Buffett:
He had an investment company,

00:10:06.034 --> 00:10:06.966
and as an adult
when I looked back,

00:10:07.166 --> 00:10:10.000
I thought, "Wow, did that ever
take a lot of nerve."

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:13.400
Sometimes we'd
go down there on Sunday,

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:15.500
and we could play
with the adding machine.

00:10:17.041 --> 00:10:20.125
My brother and I tended
to play the games together.

00:10:20.325 --> 00:10:22.841
And I remember
at one point he said to me,

00:10:23.041 --> 00:10:27.834
"I'm going to be a millionaire by the
time I'm... 30," or something like that.

00:10:28.034 --> 00:10:31.250
It was totally outside of anything
my family had experienced,

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:33.708
but he just was
unusual that way.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:39.170
Doris Buffett:
Well, I was the oldest,

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:40.841
and then my brother
and then my sister.

00:10:41.041 --> 00:10:43.800
And my father would go
to New York periodically

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.542
to check on businesses,
stocks, and things like that,

00:10:46.742 --> 00:10:48.708
and he'd come back,
he'd always have a costume

00:10:48.908 --> 00:10:51.125
for each of us,
and Warren loved it.

00:10:52.083 --> 00:10:55.175
He was very good-natured.
He was quiet.

00:10:55.375 --> 00:10:57.750
It was hard to tell
he was a genius at that point,

00:10:57.950 --> 00:10:59.917
but I mean,
who was looking?

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:06.583
Warren:
The first books I read on investment

00:11:06.783 --> 00:11:08.583
were actually
in my dad's office.

00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:12.583
Pretty soon, I read
all the books in the office

00:11:12.783 --> 00:11:14.750
and read some of them
more than once.

00:11:16.625 --> 00:11:18.504
My dad had
various nicknames for me.

00:11:18.704 --> 00:11:20.481
He'd call me
"Fireball" sometimes,

00:11:20.681 --> 00:11:22.949
because I'd start
little businesses.

00:11:23.149 --> 00:11:25.217
He didn't care
about money at all.

00:11:25.417 --> 00:11:28.050
He believed very much
in having an inner scorecard

00:11:28.250 --> 00:11:31.583
and never worry about what other
people are thinking about you.

00:11:31.783 --> 00:11:33.550
You know, just... just...

00:11:33.750 --> 00:11:37.750
if you know why you're doing what
you're doing, that's good enough.

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:39.925
I admired everything
about him to the extent

00:11:40.125 --> 00:11:43.175
that I was absorbing lessons
from him without knowing it.

00:11:43.375 --> 00:11:47.125
And the idea that all lives have
equal value is something that

00:11:47.325 --> 00:11:50.125
all three of his children
felt since I can remember.

00:11:53.708 --> 00:11:55.875
My dad at one point
ran for congress

00:11:56.075 --> 00:11:57.625
when I was 12 or so.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:00.425
It was
a very republican household.

00:12:00.625 --> 00:12:03.542
I campaigned for him.
My sisters campaigned for him.

00:12:03.742 --> 00:12:05.041
The whole family did.

00:12:08.583 --> 00:12:11.258
My mother was
very, very bright,

00:12:11.458 --> 00:12:14.625
and she was very gregarious.
She was a good campaigner for my dad.

00:12:16.125 --> 00:12:18.966
Bertie:
She had a lot of ambition,

00:12:19.166 --> 00:12:21.925
and I think
my brother Warren got a lot

00:12:22.125 --> 00:12:27.166
of his extreme competitiveness
from my mother, actually.

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:29.717
Doris:
She was brilliant at math.

00:12:29.917 --> 00:12:31.754
You know, I guess
they still had these things

00:12:31.954 --> 00:12:33.592
where you crank them
and things added up,

00:12:33.792 --> 00:12:36.917
and she could add it in her head
faster than the machine could do it.

00:12:37.117 --> 00:12:39.500
She was
absolutely amazing in that.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.625
Warren: She was very dutiful
about taking care of the kids,

00:12:43.825 --> 00:12:45.883
but you didn't get
the same feeling of... of love.

00:12:46.083 --> 00:12:49.667
It was there, but it just... it didn't
come out the same way as with my dad.

