When I'd wake up
in the morning,

00:14:25.083 --> 00:14:27.417
I'd listen to hear her voice.
I could tell by her voice

00:14:27.617 --> 00:14:30.425
if it was going to be
a terrible day or not.

00:14:30.625 --> 00:14:33.625
Warren: When she got difficult,
the three children felt it.

00:14:36.083 --> 00:14:40.125
When I was at the low point, sort of,
I decided that I would run away.

00:14:41.959 --> 00:14:44.917
So I talked two other guys
into running away with me.

00:14:46.458 --> 00:14:48.458
We went out,
and we start hitchhiking...

00:14:49.708 --> 00:14:51.508
and then we got picked up
by the highway patrol

00:14:51.708 --> 00:14:54.792
and that scared
the hell out of us.

00:14:57.083 --> 00:15:00.875
It's very interesting. My dad never
really gave me hell about doing this,

00:15:01.075 --> 00:15:02.175
but he finally said,
"You know,"

00:15:02.375 --> 00:15:05.458
he said,
"you can do better than this."

00:15:05.658 --> 00:15:08.342
And just saying that,
I mean, I...

00:15:08.542 --> 00:15:10.834
I felt like I was
letting him down, basically.

00:15:11.034 --> 00:15:13.500
So in all ways,
he was teaching me.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:16.166
Never taught
by telling me things,

00:15:16.366 --> 00:15:17.800
he just taught by example.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.333
He had unlimited confidence in me,
even when I screwed up,

00:15:21.533 --> 00:15:24.625
and that takes you
a long, long way.

00:15:28.041 --> 00:15:29.717
The best gift
I was ever given

00:15:29.917 --> 00:15:32.625
was to have the father
that I had when I was born.

00:15:38.291 --> 00:15:42.458
I didn't want to go to college.
I was 16 when I got out of high school

00:15:42.658 --> 00:15:44.175
and I was buying stocks.

00:15:44.375 --> 00:15:46.008
I mean,
I actually was having a pretty good time

00:15:46.208 --> 00:15:49.333
and I didn't see that really was much
to be gained by going to college,

00:15:49.533 --> 00:15:51.250
but my dad
kind of jollied me into it.

00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:53.217
????

00:15:53.417 --> 00:15:55.546
Doris:
He had a roommate who was a friend of mine,

00:15:55.746 --> 00:15:57.875
and the roommate said
it would just drive him crazy,

00:15:58.075 --> 00:15:59.342
because he studied
all the time,

00:15:59.542 --> 00:16:02.875
and Warren would come in
15 minutes before the exam

00:16:03.075 --> 00:16:06.008
and just ace his way
through it.

00:16:06.208 --> 00:16:09.041
Warren: I finished in three years,
'cause I had enough credits,

00:16:09.241 --> 00:16:11.500
and I was in a hurry.
I wanted to get out.

00:16:15.458 --> 00:16:17.291
Warren:
When I got out of the University of Nebraska,

00:16:17.491 --> 00:16:19.883
I applied
to Harvard Business school.

00:16:20.083 --> 00:16:24.000
They told me I was to get
interviewed in a place near Chicago.

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:28.208
I got there,
and he interviewed me for about 10 minutes,

00:16:28.408 --> 00:16:30.008
and he said, "Forget it."

00:16:30.208 --> 00:16:31.675
"You're not going
to Harvard."

00:16:31.875 --> 00:16:34.712
And so now I'm thinking,
"What do I tell my dad?

00:16:34.912 --> 00:16:37.750
Oh, this is terrible."
And it turned out to be

00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:39.208
the best thing
that ever happened to me.

00:16:39.408 --> 00:16:40.759
Later that summer,

00:16:40.959 --> 00:16:42.550
I was looking
through a catalog

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:46.583
and in the catalog, it had these
names of people that were teaching,

00:16:46.783 --> 00:16:49.500
and one was Graham
and another was Dodd.

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:51.875
I had read this book
by the two of them,

00:16:52.075 --> 00:16:54.646
so I wrote him a letter
in mid-August,

00:16:54.846 --> 00:16:57.217
and I said,
"Dear Professor Dodd,"

00:16:57.417 --> 00:16:59.592
I said, "I thought
you guys were dead."

00:16:59.792 --> 00:17:02.675
"But, now that I found out
that you're alive

00:17:02.875 --> 00:17:05.667
and teaching at Columbia,
I would really like to come."

00:17:05.867 --> 00:17:08.396
And he admitted me.
So, you know what?

00:17:08.596 --> 00:17:11.125
That... it just shows,
you never can tell.

00:17:11.325 --> 00:17:14.875
????

00:17:17.625 --> 00:17:19.550
Man: Gentlemen,
Professor Graham.

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:21.300
Warren:
Ben was this incredible teacher.

00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:25.000
I mean he... he was a natural,
and he drew us all in.

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:26.383
Are Wall Street professionals...

00:17:26.583 --> 00:17:31.008
they more accurate in the shorter
term than the long term forecast?

00:17:31.208 --> 00:17:36.708
Well, our studies indicate that you have
your choice between tossing coins...

00:17:36.908 --> 00:17:39.383
and taking the consensus
of expert opinions,

00:17:39.583 --> 00:17:43.041
and the results are just
about the same in each case.

00:17:44.291 --> 00:17:45.425
Warren:
It was like learning baseball

00:17:45.625 --> 00:17:47.841
from a fellow
who's batting .400.

00:17:48.041 --> 00:17:50.625
It really... it shaped
my professional life.

00:17:53.291 --> 00:17:56.583
There are two rules of
investing according to Warren,

00:17:56.783 --> 00:17:59.125
and he learned this
from Ben Graham.

00:17:59.325 --> 00:18:01.458
????

00:18:02.708 --> 00:18:05.467
Rule number one,
never lose money.

00:18:05.667 --> 00:18:09.333
Rule number two,
never forget rule number one.

00:18:11.667 --> 00:18:15.542
Ben Graham basically coined
the term "value investing."

00:18:15.742 --> 00:18:18.175
He believed
in careful scrutiny

00:18:18.375 --> 00:18:20.883
of a company's
financial statements,

00:18:21.083 --> 00:18:25.500
and that if you bought value,
it would eventually prove out.

00:18:28.417 --> 00:18:31.300
A few years ago,
I went to Amazon,

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.759
and sure enough,
they had this manual there,

00:18:32.959 --> 00:18:37.208
so while reliving my youth...
other guys were going to Amazon

00:18:37.408 --> 00:18:40.792
and probably buying
old "Playboys" or something,

00:18:40.992 --> 00:18:42.675
but I bought old
Moody's manuals instead,

00:18:42.875 --> 00:18:46.708
and when I got out of school,
I started selling stocks,

00:18:46.908 --> 00:18:48.342
I was 20 years old at the time,

00:18:48.542 --> 00:18:50.634
looked about 16,
and acted about 12,

00:18:50.834 --> 00:18:54.875
so I was not the most impressive
salesperson anybody ever met.

00:18:55.075 --> 00:18:58.166
But what I would do was I went
through, page by page,

00:18:58.366 --> 00:19:01.333
looking for possibly
undervalued stocks.

00:19:02.875 --> 00:19:05.375
Peter Kunhardt: Is this like going
through an old family album?

00:19:05.575 --> 00:19:07.521
Better!

00:19:07.721 --> 00:19:09.667
????

00:19:11.250 --> 00:19:13.925
When I got out of business
school at Columbia,

00:19:14.125 --> 00:19:17.566
I developed pretty decent
skills in terms of business,

00:19:17.766 --> 00:19:21.208
but I hadn't really come to
terms with the world exactly.

00:19:22.542 --> 00:19:24.592
Kunhardt:
What were you like around girls back then?

00:19:24.792 --> 00:19:29.333
Bad. I was... I was sort of out of the
swing of things there for a while.

00:19:30.542 --> 00:19:34.300
I went to my 60th reunion,
and there was a girl there.

00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:37.691
I took her out one time to the
Uptown Theater in Washington,

00:19:37.891 --> 00:19:41.083
and I asked her whether she
remembered what movie we saw,

00:19:41.283 --> 00:19:42.634
and she said,
"No, I don't remember that."

00:19:42.834 --> 00:19:45.375
And then she said,
"But I do remember one thing."

00:19:45.575 --> 00:19:47.383
And like an idiot,
I said, "What was that?"

00:19:47.583 --> 00:19:49.583
And she said, "Well,
you picked me up in a hearse."

00:19:49.783 --> 00:19:50.966
And it was true
that I owned

00:19:51.166 --> 00:19:53.667
a half-interest in a hearse
while I was in high school,

00:19:53.867 --> 00:19:55.750
which was not
the smoothest thing that...

00:19:55.950 --> 00:19:57.833
or coolest,
as they would say now...

00:19:58.033 --> 00:19:59.917
that you could...
you could do on a date.

00:20:03.458 --> 00:20:06.417
There were two turning
points in my life.

00:20:06.617 --> 00:20:07.592
Once when
I came out of the womb,

00:20:07.792 --> 00:20:09.625
and once when I met
Susie, basically.

00:20:09.825 --> 00:20:13.342
????

00:20:13.542 --> 00:20:15.375
She was the girl, yep.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:18.050
But it took her
a little longer

00:20:18.250 --> 00:20:20.708
to figure out
I was the boy.

00:20:23.458 --> 00:20:25.008
Susie Buffett:
I was going to be

00:20:25.208 --> 00:20:28.091
his youngest sister's roommate
at Northwestern.

00:20:28.291 --> 00:20:32.333
So I walk into their house,
he was sitting in this chair,

00:20:32.533 --> 00:20:35.966
and he made
some sarcastic quip.

00:20:36.166 --> 00:20:39.583
So I made one back.
I thought, "Who is this jerk?"

00:20:39.783 --> 00:20:40.634
????

00:20:40.834 --> 00:20:42.917
And that's how we met, yes.

00:20:45.750 --> 00:20:48.917
Listen, Warren is smarter
than you even know.

00:20:49.117 --> 00:20:51.959
His brain is going
all the time.

00:20:52.159 --> 00:20:54.342
And my dad said to me,

00:20:54.542 --> 00:20:56.592
"Now you have
to understand about him...

00:20:56.792 --> 00:20:59.041
"you're not going to have
discussions with him

00:20:59.241 --> 00:21:01.000
"like you would
most normal people,

00:21:01.200 --> 00:21:03.583
but he has
a heart of gold."

00:21:05.458 --> 00:21:07.708
He was just
totally enamored of her,

00:21:07.908 --> 00:21:09.966
and why not?
And she of him.

00:21:10.166 --> 00:21:13.792
She'd sit on his lap all the time,
and he'd stroke her hair.

00:21:14.792 --> 00:21:16.166
It was softening him.

00:21:17.458 --> 00:21:20.046
Susie was
really kind, considerate,

00:21:20.246 --> 00:21:22.834
and she was
the balancing force.

00:21:26.250 --> 00:21:29.041
Warren: I just got very,
very, very lucky.

00:21:29.241 --> 00:21:30.841
But I was
a lopsided person,

00:21:31.041 --> 00:21:33.542
and it took a while,
but she just stood there

00:21:33.742 --> 00:21:36.175
with a little watering can

00:21:36.375 --> 00:21:40.708
and just nourished me along
and... and changed me.

00:21:40.908 --> 00:21:43.091
????

00:21:43.291 --> 00:21:45.759
Somebody once said
that the chains of habit

00:21:45.959 --> 00:21:49.708
are too light to be felt until
they're too heavy to be broken.

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:55.000
I had been terrified
of public speaking.

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:56.625
I couldn't do it.
I'd throw up.

00:21:57.875 --> 00:22:00.875
And I knew if I didn't cure it then,
I'd never cure it.

00:22:01.075 --> 00:22:02.508
????

00:22:02.708 --> 00:22:06.629
And so I saw an ad in the paper
for the Dale Carnegie Course,

00:22:06.829 --> 00:22:10.750
which worked on developing your
ability to speak in public,

00:22:10.950 --> 00:22:11.717
and I went down there.

00:22:11.917 --> 00:22:13.800
Dale Carnegie:
Be sincere.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:15.841
A good smile
has the same effect

00:22:16.041 --> 00:22:17.717
as a puppy's tail.
When a puppy wags...

00:22:17.917 --> 00:22:20.046
Warren:
They made us do all these crazy things

00:22:20.246 --> 00:22:22.375
to get out of ourselves,
and so we stood on tables

00:22:22.575 --> 00:22:23.792
and did all kinds of things.

00:22:29.041 --> 00:22:30.837
Warren:
If I hadn't had done that...

00:22:31.037 --> 00:22:32.834
my whole life
would have been different.

00:22:34.291 --> 00:22:36.383
So in my office
you will not see

00:22:36.583 --> 00:22:38.592
the degree I got from the
University of Nebraska.

00:22:38.792 --> 00:22:41.959
You will not see the Masters degree
I got from Columbia University,

00:22:42.159 --> 00:22:44.667
but you'll see
the little award certificate

00:22:44.867 --> 00:22:47.083
I got
from the Dale Carnegie Course.

00:22:48.583 --> 00:22:50.900
As a matter of fact,
every week,

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:53.217
the instructor
would give a pencil

00:22:53.417 --> 00:22:57.834
to whoever had done the most with
what we'd learned the week before.

00:22:58.034 --> 00:23:00.250
And so in the fourth
or fifth week,

00:23:00.450 --> 00:23:02.425
I proposed to her mother,

00:23:02.625 --> 00:23:05.692
and she said yes.
And so that week,

00:23:05.892 --> 00:23:08.759
I won the pencil,
I also got engaged,

00:23:08.959 --> 00:23:10.792
and it was
an incredible week.

00:23:10.992 --> 00:23:12.291
????

00:23:16.291 --> 00:23:18.004
Warren:
The wedding date was kind of interesting,

00:23:18.204 --> 00:23:19.917
because I couldn't see
anything without my glasses,

00:23:20.117 --> 00:23:20.966
and I was
so nervous that I...

00:23:21.166 --> 00:23:23.508
I just decided
to take off my glasses

00:23:23.708 --> 00:23:26.625
and I wouldn't be able to see
all those people out there.

00:23:26.825 --> 00:23:30.917
????

00:23:33.375 --> 00:23:35.959
She was 19 when we got
married and I was 21...

00:23:37.625 --> 00:23:41.333
but she was so much more mature than I was.
There was no comparison.

00:23:46.667 --> 00:23:48.333
She was a better person
than I was...

00:23:49.667 --> 00:23:51.834
but when you get married,
it's not a question of saying,

00:23:52.034 --> 00:23:54.834
"I'm going to put
a 14% factor in for humor,

00:23:55.034 --> 00:23:57.834
and 17% for intellect,
and 22% for looks."

00:23:58.034 --> 00:24:00.175
It doesn't work that way.

00:24:00.375 --> 00:24:03.750
I knew it was the right decision, and...
and it was.

00:24:12.875 --> 00:24:14.834
Woman:
You could live anywhere in the world.

00:24:15.034 --> 00:24:16.091
Why do you choose
Omaha, Nebraska?

00:24:16.291 --> 00:24:19.045
Yeah, I love it, and I...
you know, I was...

00:24:19.245 --> 00:24:21.689
born about a mile from here
and, you know,

00:24:21.889 --> 00:24:24.333
I've never had a bad
experience in Omaha.

00:24:24.533 --> 00:24:27.792
????

00:24:36.542 --> 00:24:39.208
Well, Omaha and Nebraska
are home to me.

00:24:41.500 --> 00:24:43.458
Everything about it
seems like home.

00:24:45.625 --> 00:24:49.634
It's a pace,
it's relationships.

00:24:49.834 --> 00:24:53.041
There's a lot of continuity.
There's a lot of community.

00:24:53.241 --> 00:24:54.300
There's a lot
of friendship.

00:24:54.500 --> 00:24:56.800
It's a very solid place
and friendly place

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.917
in which to grow up in,
in which to conduct a business.

00:25:04.667 --> 00:25:07.442
When I came back
to Omaha in early 1956,

00:25:07.642 --> 00:25:10.417
I had no idea
what I was going to do.

00:25:11.875 --> 00:25:15.000
A few months after I came back,
some members of the family said,

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:16.312
"What should we do
with our money?"

00:25:16.512 --> 00:25:17.656
And I said, "Well,
I'm not going back

00:25:17.856 --> 00:25:18.800
"in the business
of selling stocks,

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.333
but if you would like
to join me in a partnership,"

00:25:21.533 --> 00:25:22.300
I said,
"I'll be glad to do it."

00:25:22.500 --> 00:25:24.959
So within a couple of months
after coming back,

00:25:25.159 --> 00:25:26.625
I set up
the first partnership.

00:25:26.825 --> 00:25:28.834
????

00:25:33.333 --> 00:25:35.333
I wrote
all the checks individually.

00:25:35.533 --> 00:25:37.008
I filed
11 income-tax returns.

00:25:37.208 --> 00:25:40.125
I took delivery on stocks for
all these different companies.

00:25:40.325 --> 00:25:43.542
I...
I was a one-man band there for six years.

00:25:47.208 --> 00:25:50.583
Sandy Gottesman: Warren would sit
upstairs in his little office there,

00:25:50.783 --> 00:25:53.500
and I would bring up
the name of a company,

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:54.800
and most of the time he knew

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:56.796
much more than I did
about the company.

00:25:56.996 --> 00:25:58.592
He'd know how many shares
were outstanding.

00:25:58.792 --> 00:26:01.166
He'd know the capitalization.
He'd know the earnings.

00:26:01.366 --> 00:26:04.217
It was absolutely incredible.

00:26:04.417 --> 00:26:07.542
I mean when Warren said something,
it meant a heck of a lot,

00:26:07.742 --> 00:26:10.542
and I think all of us paid
a lot of attention to Warren

00:26:10.742 --> 00:26:13.792
when he took a definite
stand on something.

00:26:15.542 --> 00:26:19.834
Charlie Munger:
When I first met Warren back in 1959,

00:26:20.034 --> 00:26:21.091
I recognized immediately

00:26:21.291 --> 00:26:24.708
that he was
a very intelligent person.

00:26:24.908 --> 00:26:26.342
For the last four
or five years,

00:26:26.542 --> 00:26:28.650
the stock market
has been booming along

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:30.959
and presumably
forecasting better business,

00:26:31.159 --> 00:26:32.342
which has really
not materialized,

00:26:32.542 --> 00:26:35.083
so maybe the stock market
is really correcting

00:26:35.283 --> 00:26:37.145
a previous incorrect
forecast this time

00:26:37.345 --> 00:26:39.008
rather than making
a new correct one.

00:26:39.208 --> 00:26:43.708
He made a lot of money
buying thinly traded securities

00:26:43.908 --> 00:26:47.125
that were incredibly
cheap statistically.

00:26:47.325 --> 00:26:48.667
????

00:26:50.708 --> 00:26:52.166
Loomis:
Warren was, at that time,

00:26:52.366 --> 00:26:53.550
dealing with small companies,

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:57.316
and his investments often were
to buy a company

00:26:57.516 --> 00:27:01.083
that you could figure was
a discarded cigar butt,

00:27:01.283 --> 00:27:02.717
but it had
one more smoke in it,

00:27:02.917 --> 00:27:06.129
and he wanted
to buy at the right time

00:27:06.329 --> 00:27:09.585
to be able to benefit
from the one smoke.

00:27:09.785 --> 00:27:12.841
The first partnership
started with $105,100.

00:27:13.041 --> 00:27:16.816
I put up the 100,
and the other people put up the 105,000.

00:27:17.016 --> 00:27:20.792
And then at the start of 1962,
I moved to Kiewit Plaza.

00:27:20.992 --> 00:27:23.583
And by the time I moved
to Kiewit Plaza,

00:27:23.783 --> 00:27:25.687
we had $7 million invested,

00:27:25.887 --> 00:27:27.792
and a fair amount
was profits.

00:27:27.992 --> 00:27:31.508
????

00:27:31.708 --> 00:27:35.375
I was then renting a house.
I never owned a house to that point.

00:27:36.542 --> 00:27:37.634
And then two years later,

00:27:37.834 --> 00:27:41.333
I bought the house
I live in today in 1958.

00:27:49.208 --> 00:27:51.333
We had three children,
Susie and I.

00:27:55.291 --> 00:27:56.425
And we had 'em young,
incidentally,

00:27:56.625 --> 00:27:58.333
which was I think was
a very good thing.

00:27:58.533 --> 00:28:00.834
????

00:28:03.750 --> 00:28:05.583
My daughter Susie
was born here.

00:28:07.083 --> 00:28:09.583
I named her Susie just like that,
as soon as I looked at her,

00:28:09.783 --> 00:28:11.166
because she looked
just like her mother,

00:28:11.366 --> 00:28:15.217
????

00:28:15.417 --> 00:28:17.250
And she was a cinch.

00:28:20.083 --> 00:28:24.917
And then Howie was, you know,
this absolute bundle of energy...

00:28:26.250 --> 00:28:28.375
which made things
very difficult

00:28:28.575 --> 00:28:30.542
for big Susie
for a while.

00:28:33.625 --> 00:28:36.542
Peter again reverted back
to Susie's personality,

00:28:36.742 --> 00:28:38.291
and he was an easy child.

00:28:43.291 --> 00:28:45.542
Howard Buffett: Well,
I would describe my childhood as normal,

00:28:45.742 --> 00:28:47.792
but who knows
what normal is?

00:28:47.992 --> 00:28:49.008
People often think,

00:28:49.208 --> 00:28:51.875
"Well, Warren Buffett was
this famous rich guy."

00:28:52.075 --> 00:28:53.375
He was not famous,
and he wasn't rich

00:28:53.575 --> 00:28:54.625
when we were growing up.

00:28:54.825 --> 00:28:56.342
????

00:28:56.542 --> 00:29:00.258
What I saw first and foremost,

00:29:00.458 --> 00:29:03.342
day in and day out,
was consistency.

00:29:03.542 --> 00:29:06.837
Every day we hear the garage
door close in the house

00:29:07.037 --> 00:29:10.333
and then like clockwork,
my dad would come in the door,

00:29:10.533 --> 00:29:13.708
"I'm home!" and we'd
all eat dinner together,

00:29:13.908 --> 00:29:16.000
which I think surprises
a lot of people.

00:29:18.667 --> 00:29:21.208
Susie Buffett, Jr. : My dad,
he used to rock me to sleep at night

00:29:21.408 --> 00:29:23.550
and sing "Over the Rainbow,"
so I have

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:26.920
this insanely sentimental
attachment to that song.

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:30.291
I've always had a really close
relationship with him.

00:29:30.491 --> 00:29:33.083
????

00:29:36.166 --> 00:29:37.667
Warren:
I've got three very different kids,

00:29:37.867 --> 00:29:39.646
and they've got
a common heart,

00:29:39.846 --> 00:29:41.625
which they got
from their mother.

00:29:44.208 --> 00:29:45.691
She did most
of the work by far

00:29:45.891 --> 00:29:47.179
of bringing up
the children,

00:29:47.379 --> 00:29:48.467
which is probably
a good thing.

00:29:48.667 --> 00:29:50.875
They have more
of her qualities than mine,

00:29:51.075 --> 00:29:53.333
which I would...
I would recommend.

00:29:54.792 --> 00:29:55.800
Howard:
Well, my mom was

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.383
the biggest part
of my life growing up...

00:29:58.583 --> 00:30:01.375
even though I got disciplined
on a regular basis

00:30:01.575 --> 00:30:03.041
and she was usually
the one doing it,

00:30:03.241 --> 00:30:04.800
she was still
my best friend.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.050
She was somebody
who would help anybody,

00:30:07.250 --> 00:30:08.759
I mean,
whether she knew 'em or didn't know 'em

00:30:08.959 --> 00:30:12.542
or maybe even didn't agree with them,
she would still help them.

00:30:14.083 --> 00:30:15.883
Warren:
She was incredibly empathetic,

00:30:16.083 --> 00:30:20.458
and she was interested
in every person individually.

00:30:20.658 --> 00:30:24.375
She never cared about money
or business at all.

00:30:24.575 --> 00:30:25.717
Susie:
I mean he would go around saying,

00:30:25.917 --> 00:30:29.046
"I'm going to be the
richest man in the world."

00:30:29.246 --> 00:30:32.064
And I think, well,
it's like somebody says,

00:30:32.264 --> 00:30:35.386
"I play music,
and I'm gonna be Mozart."

00:30:35.586 --> 00:30:38.708
I don't know.
How does anyone know...

00:30:39.458 --> 00:30:41.425
How does anyone know?
You know?

00:30:41.625 --> 00:30:46.041
So that was okay.
I don't really care about that.

00:30:47.375 --> 00:30:49.542
Loomis:
I would say that Susie led Warren

00:30:49.742 --> 00:30:51.562
toward changing
his political views.

00:30:51.762 --> 00:30:53.383
He grew up
as a young Republican,

00:30:53.583 --> 00:30:56.525
his father was
a Republican congressman,

00:30:56.725 --> 00:30:59.667
but Susie saw things
in different ways.

00:30:59.867 --> 00:31:01.175
She was the catalyst.

00:31:01.375 --> 00:31:04.841
Freedom, freedom, freedom!

00:31:05.041 --> 00:31:07.592
Louder, louder,
louder, louder, louder!

00:31:07.792 --> 00:31:10.525
Freedom, freedom...
What do we want now?

00:31:10.725 --> 00:31:13.458
Susie:
When the children were growing up,

00:31:13.658 --> 00:31:16.217
I was very involved
in civil rights.

00:31:16.417 --> 00:31:21.583
I was immersed in it, and I think
that's what made Warren a Democrat.

00:31:21.783 --> 00:31:25.291
He would go with me
to hear speakers.

00:31:26.625 --> 00:31:29.091
Warren: I remember that speech
that Martin Luther King gave.

00:31:29.291 --> 00:31:33.375
That was one of the most inspiring
speeches I... I've ever heard.

00:31:33.575 --> 00:31:35.175
I come to say to you
this afternoon...

00:31:35.375 --> 00:31:37.834
Warren: Took me right out of my seat.
My wife was with me.

00:31:38.034 --> 00:31:39.175
We both had
the same experience.

00:31:39.375 --> 00:31:42.275
Martin Luther King: It will not be long.
It was interesting, he...

00:31:42.475 --> 00:31:46.575
in that speech, he talked about
truth forever on the scaffold,

00:31:46.775 --> 00:31:50.875
long forever on the throne,
but that scaffold sways the future.

00:31:51.075 --> 00:31:53.250
Well, he was going
to be dead in six months,

00:31:53.450 --> 00:31:55.458
but that scaffold
did sway the future.

00:31:57.291 --> 00:31:59.191
My wife was
more active than I was,

00:31:59.391 --> 00:32:01.091
but I was 100%
with her mentally.

00:32:01.291 --> 00:32:04.754
I was just working a little
more on my own investments.

00:32:04.954 --> 00:32:08.417
But it didn't make a difference
what we were gonna do

00:32:08.617 --> 00:32:09.800
with the money
after we made it.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:11.717
I thought I would pile
it up over the years

00:32:11.917 --> 00:32:16.041
then she would unpile it
in terms of running a...

00:32:16.241 --> 00:32:17.925
one very large foundation.

00:32:18.125 --> 00:32:21.254
And I was particularly good
at compounding money,

00:32:21.454 --> 00:32:24.583
and therefore society
would benefit by waiting.

00:32:24.783 --> 00:32:26.750
????

00:32:28.208 --> 00:32:31.717
I was genetically blessed
with certain wiring

00:32:31.917 --> 00:32:34.667
that's very useful in a
highly-developed market system

00:32:34.867 --> 00:32:36.467
where there's lots
of chips on the table,

00:32:36.667 --> 00:32:39.583
and you know, I happen
to be good at that game.

00:32:41.625 --> 00:32:43.917
Ted Williams wrote a book
called "The Science of Hitting,"

00:32:44.117 --> 00:32:46.467
and in it he had a picture
of himself at bat

00:32:46.667 --> 00:32:51.667
and the strike zone broken
into, I think, 77 squares.

00:32:51.867 --> 00:32:53.425
And he said,
if he waited for the pitch

00:32:53.625 --> 00:32:56.300
that was really in his sweet spot,
he would bat .400

00:32:56.500 --> 00:32:59.291
and if he had to swing at
something on the lower corner,

00:32:59.491 --> 00:33:01.675
he would
probably bat .235.

00:33:01.875 --> 00:33:05.083
And in investing,
I'm in a no-called strike business,

00:33:05.283 --> 00:33:07.133
which is the best business
you can be in.

00:33:07.333 --> 00:33:09.008
I can look at a thousand
different companies,

00:33:09.208 --> 00:33:13.250
and I don't have to be right on every
one of them or even 50 of 'em...

00:33:14.583 --> 00:33:16.500
so I can pick the ball
I want to hit.

00:33:18.417 --> 00:33:23.333
And the trick in investing is just to sit
there and watch pitch after pitch to go by

00:33:23.533 --> 00:33:25.008
and wait for the one
right in your sweet spot.

00:33:25.208 --> 00:33:28.000
And the people that are yelling,
"Swing, you bum"? Ignore 'em.

00:33:29.250 --> 00:33:32.542
There's a temptation
for people to act

00:33:32.742 --> 00:33:33.925
far too frequently in stocks,

00:33:34.125 --> 00:33:36.508
simply because
they're so liquid.

00:33:36.708 --> 00:33:39.175
Over the years
you develop a lot of filters,

00:33:39.375 --> 00:33:42.417
and I do know what I call
my circle of competence,

00:33:42.617 --> 00:33:44.550
so I-I... I stay
within that circle,

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:48.583
and I don't worry about things
that are outside that circle.

00:33:48.783 --> 00:33:50.383
Defining what your game is,

00:33:50.583 --> 00:33:54.417
where you're going to have an
edge is enormously important.

00:33:58.041 --> 00:34:02.175
