00:34:02.375 --> 00:34:05.417
I bought the first shares
of Berkshire in 1962,

00:34:05.617 --> 00:34:07.396
and it was
a northern textile business

00:34:07.596 --> 00:34:09.175
destined to become
extinct eventually,

00:34:09.375 --> 00:34:14.250
and it was a statistically cheap
stock in a terrible business.

00:34:15.625 --> 00:34:18.091
Berkshire Hathaway
was closing mills

00:34:18.291 --> 00:34:21.792
and as they closed mills,
it would free up some capital,

00:34:21.992 --> 00:34:23.792
and then they would
repurchase shares,

00:34:23.992 --> 00:34:25.592
so I bought
some stock with the idea

00:34:25.792 --> 00:34:28.458
that there would be another
tender offer at some point,

00:34:28.658 --> 00:34:31.708
and we would sell the stock
at a modest profit.

00:34:31.908 --> 00:34:33.883
And at one point,

00:34:34.083 --> 00:34:37.333
the management asked me at what
price we would tender our stock,

00:34:37.533 --> 00:34:39.166
and I said, "$11.50."

00:34:39.366 --> 00:34:41.800
????

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.834
And the tender offer
came out a few months later,

00:34:45.034 --> 00:34:49.175
and it was
at $11 and 3/8ths,

00:34:49.375 --> 00:34:51.500
which was an eighth
of a point cheaper.

00:34:52.458 --> 00:34:53.634
And that made me very mad,

00:34:53.834 --> 00:34:56.634
so I just started
buying more stock.

00:34:56.834 --> 00:35:00.458
I just felt that I'd been
double-crossed by the management.

00:35:00.658 --> 00:35:02.966
And in May of 1965,

00:35:03.166 --> 00:35:05.667
I bought enough so we
controlled the company,

00:35:05.867 --> 00:35:07.583
and we changed
the management.

00:35:14.083 --> 00:35:17.066
It was a pretty silly way
to behave,

00:35:17.266 --> 00:35:19.491
as Warren has recounted
in retrospect.

00:35:19.691 --> 00:35:22.079
One of the reasons
Warren is successful

00:35:22.279 --> 00:35:24.467
is he's brutal
in appraising his own past.

00:35:24.667 --> 00:35:29.458
He wants to identify misthinkings
and avoid them in the future,

00:35:29.658 --> 00:35:32.562
but it was an accident that
he chose Berkshire Hathaway.

00:35:32.762 --> 00:35:35.467
If the chairman hadn't tried
to cheat him out of an eighth,

00:35:35.667 --> 00:35:39.667
there wouldn't have been any
Buffett- Berkshire Hathaway history.

00:35:42.166 --> 00:35:45.458
Warren: If you're emotional about investment,
you're not going to do well.

00:35:45.658 --> 00:35:47.958
You may have all these
feelings about the stock.

00:35:48.158 --> 00:35:50.258
The stock has
no feelings about you.

00:35:50.458 --> 00:35:52.258
Looking back, it's interesting,
that tender offer...

00:35:52.458 --> 00:35:56.834
I didn't realize it, but it... it happened
about five days after my dad had died

00:35:57.034 --> 00:35:59.875
and whether that had affected me or not,
I don't know.

00:36:00.075 --> 00:36:02.333
????

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:07.208
Kunhardt: Do you remember your last
conversation with your father?

00:36:07.408 --> 00:36:09.583
Yeah, but I don't want
to talk about it.

00:36:16.667 --> 00:36:19.708
Munger:
I think it just sobered him and hurt him,

00:36:20.708 --> 00:36:22.083
but...

00:36:24.375 --> 00:36:25.917
Warren soldiers on.

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:32.133
Both Warren and I
could look at our fathers

00:36:32.333 --> 00:36:35.258
and see what they did right
and what they did wrong.

00:36:35.458 --> 00:36:40.375
Warren's father was a real
old-fashioned right-wing ideologue.

00:36:41.375 --> 00:36:43.508
And his father was
so intense about it,

00:36:43.708 --> 00:36:46.883
that Warren just decided
that it was mistake...

00:36:47.083 --> 00:36:50.150
it cabbaged up your head
to be that much an ideologue,

00:36:50.350 --> 00:36:53.417
so he loved his father,
but he didn't want to become

00:36:53.617 --> 00:36:56.792
that much of a true believer in...
in anything.

00:36:59.375 --> 00:37:04.542
My politics became more overt
after my dad died.

00:37:04.742 --> 00:37:06.258
????

00:37:06.458 --> 00:37:08.467
Civil rights
changed my views.

00:37:08.667 --> 00:37:11.050
You know, in 1776
Thomas Jefferson wrote,

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:14.125
"All men are created equal,"
and then when they wrote the Constitution,

00:37:14.325 --> 00:37:15.841
they all of a sudden
decided that, no,

00:37:16.041 --> 00:37:18.125
it was just 3/5ths of a person
if you were black.

00:37:18.325 --> 00:37:19.583
I mean, that struck me
as kind of crazy.

00:37:19.783 --> 00:37:22.050
????

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:26.000
Susie: I was talking to him one
day about some racial issue,

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:30.583
and he said to me,
"Wait till women discover

00:37:30.783 --> 00:37:33.083
they're the slaves
of the world."

00:37:34.250 --> 00:37:38.166
Now how many men
were cognizant of that,

00:37:38.366 --> 00:37:40.083
and even women then?

00:37:42.208 --> 00:37:44.750
Warren:
The initial example is really my mother.

00:37:44.950 --> 00:37:46.550
She came from a generation

00:37:46.750 --> 00:37:48.879
where the main function
of the wife

00:37:49.079 --> 00:37:51.008
was to help
her husband in the job.

00:37:51.208 --> 00:37:54.587
And my sisters are
fully as smart as I am.

00:37:54.787 --> 00:37:57.966
They got better personalities
than I had,

00:37:58.166 --> 00:38:00.667
but they got the message
a million different ways

00:38:00.867 --> 00:38:02.966
that their future
was limited,

00:38:03.166 --> 00:38:05.592
and I got the message
that the sky is the limit

00:38:05.792 --> 00:38:09.375
and it wasn't due to a lack of
love or anything of the sort.

00:38:09.575 --> 00:38:11.125
It just...
it was the culture.

00:38:13.041 --> 00:38:14.175
On the other hand,
you can look

00:38:14.375 --> 00:38:16.275
at the flip side of that
and say it's quite encouraging,

00:38:16.475 --> 00:38:18.375
because if you look at what
this country accomplished

00:38:18.575 --> 00:38:19.800
only using half of its talent,

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:21.592
just think of the potential
for the future.

00:38:21.792 --> 00:38:24.166
I'm enormously bullish
on America over the future

00:38:24.366 --> 00:38:26.187
and part of the reason
is that we,

00:38:26.387 --> 00:38:28.008
by some rather
stupid decisions,

00:38:28.208 --> 00:38:30.834
essentially put half our
talent on the sidelines.

00:38:32.333 --> 00:38:36.291
Loomis: Warren is probably the most
rational person I've ever met.

00:38:36.491 --> 00:38:39.792
Charlie Munger
would be a close rival.

