00:38:41.708 --> 00:38:44.899
that Warren
depended on heavily

00:38:45.099 --> 00:38:47.908
and I think his first
experiences

00:38:48.108 --> 00:38:50.717
in the discarded-
cigar-butt era

00:38:50.917 --> 00:38:55.708
convinced him that it was not
exactly where he wanted to be.

00:38:55.908 --> 00:38:57.999
Munger:
He made so much money for so long

00:38:58.199 --> 00:39:00.353
doing what he'd been taught
by Ben Graham,

00:39:00.553 --> 00:39:02.508
which he'd buy
these very cheap stocks.

00:39:02.708 --> 00:39:04.583
If they were cheap enough,
he didn't care it was

00:39:04.783 --> 00:39:06.091
a lousy company
and a lousy management.

00:39:06.291 --> 00:39:10.917
He knew he was going to make money anyway,
just because of the cheapness.

00:39:11.117 --> 00:39:13.217
Warren:
Charlie Munger has had a big impact on me

00:39:13.417 --> 00:39:18.583
in moving me toward looking for
wonderful companies at fair prices

00:39:18.783 --> 00:39:21.050
rather than fair companies
at wonderful prices.

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:25.542
That was enormously important, because it
enabled Berkshire to scale up in a way

00:39:25.742 --> 00:39:28.708
that would have been
impossible to do otherwise.

00:39:29.792 --> 00:39:32.258
Yep?
