The ideal way to run a
headquarters is to have one man,

00:41:46.325 --> 00:41:48.175
preferably over 80,

00:41:48.375 --> 00:41:51.296
sitting in an office
by himself.

00:41:51.496 --> 00:41:54.217
Anything else
is pure frippery.

00:41:54.417 --> 00:41:56.583
Warren:
He's always honest in what he tells me,

00:41:56.783 --> 00:41:58.417
so I... I listen to him.

00:42:00.583 --> 00:42:02.250
Munger:
We never had an argument.

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:04.542
We just...

00:42:06.083 --> 00:42:09.217
We just kinda
roll with it easily.

00:42:09.417 --> 00:42:13.442
Suppose Warren doesn't wanna do
something that I would've done,

00:42:13.642 --> 00:42:17.667
and suppose that happens four
times over 40 years or something.

00:42:17.867 --> 00:42:19.959
What the hell difference
does it make to me?

00:42:20.159 --> 00:42:21.383
????

00:42:21.583 --> 00:42:23.917
Net, the record is
working out is fine.

00:42:28.458 --> 00:42:33.125
Both of us know that we've
done better by having ethics.

00:42:33.325 --> 00:42:34.425
Warren's not interested

00:42:34.625 --> 00:42:36.458
in making money
by cheating people.

00:42:39.458 --> 00:42:40.550
Loomis:
Warren's opinions

00:42:40.750 --> 00:42:43.133
of Wall Street
investment bankers

00:42:43.333 --> 00:42:46.566
would not endear him
to their mothers.

00:42:46.766 --> 00:42:50.000
He feels that they're,
for the most part,

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:51.675
not out for their clients.

00:42:51.875 --> 00:42:55.125
They're out for their own
business interests.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:59.667
Warren: In the late 1960s,
there were just a flood

00:42:59.867 --> 00:43:02.883
of accounting
shenanigans and mergers

00:43:03.083 --> 00:43:06.834
built upon false accounting
and misleading people.

00:43:07.034 --> 00:43:09.792
It was a time
when a lot of charlatans

00:43:09.992 --> 00:43:11.467
were prevailing in Wall Street

00:43:11.667 --> 00:43:13.650
and were being applauded
by Wall Street.

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:15.834
I understood what
the game was about,

00:43:16.034 --> 00:43:17.091
but I didn't want
to play in it,

00:43:17.291 --> 00:43:21.133
so I closed down the
partnership at the end of 1969,

00:43:21.333 --> 00:43:25.166
and I took on the title of
Chairman for Berkshire Hathaway.

00:43:25.366 --> 00:43:28.091
????

00:43:28.291 --> 00:43:30.254
Munger: Well, I think
the modern Berkshire

00:43:30.454 --> 00:43:32.417
is pretty much
all a reflection of Warren.

00:43:32.617 --> 00:43:34.841
????

00:43:35.041 --> 00:43:38.920
I have constructed
a business that fits me.

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:42.800
It's kind of crazy
to spend your life painting

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:44.917
if you're painting a subject
you don't want to look at.

00:43:45.117 --> 00:43:48.208
I've gotten to paint
my own painting in business

00:43:48.408 --> 00:43:50.708
on an unlimited
canvas in a way.

00:43:52.542 --> 00:43:54.291
It's a different
sort of place.

00:43:55.875 --> 00:43:57.175
I work with a great
group of people

00:43:57.375 --> 00:44:00.834
that make my life very easy
and that take good care of me.

00:44:01.034 --> 00:44:03.000
Come. Okay.

00:44:04.166 --> 00:44:06.383
We have 25 people
in the office,

00:44:06.583 --> 00:44:12.208
and if you go back, it's the exact same 25,
the exact same ones.

00:44:13.542 --> 00:44:15.504
We don't have any
committees at Berkshire.

00:44:15.704 --> 00:44:17.467
We don't have
a public relations department.

00:44:17.667 --> 00:44:20.125
We don't have investor relations.
We don't have a general council.

00:44:20.325 --> 00:44:21.800
We don't have
a human relations department.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:26.250
We just don't go for anything that
people do just as a matter of form.

00:44:27.458 --> 00:44:29.250
It's exactly the life I like,

00:44:29.450 --> 00:44:31.800
and it's not work to me.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.166
It's just a form
of play, basically.

00:44:43.333 --> 00:44:45.383
Oh, I...
I like things quiet.

00:44:45.583 --> 00:44:47.050
I shut the door,
actually, at the office,

00:44:47.250 --> 00:44:49.400
'cause I don't want to hear
anybody talking outside.

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:51.750
Woman on TV:
Broad distinctions between his views

00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:53.479
and the belt-tightening
proposals.

00:44:53.679 --> 00:44:55.114
Warren:
And I still probably spend

00:44:55.314 --> 00:44:56.550
five or six hours
a day reading.

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:58.417
Woman on TV:
...look at what's trending today.

00:44:58.617 --> 00:44:59.634
Our quick round-up...

00:44:59.834 --> 00:45:02.125
Howard: Well,
what's amazing is the stuff he remembers.

00:45:03.166 --> 00:45:05.091
It's like a little computer,
you know?

00:45:05.291 --> 00:45:08.417
I keep thinking the hard drive will
run out of space, but it doesn't.

00:45:10.667 --> 00:45:13.000
Melinda Gates:
He's one of the smartest people we know.

00:45:13.200 --> 00:45:14.917
So I was at a couple
of the family dinners

00:45:15.117 --> 00:45:16.646
at the Gates house
where Mary, Bill's mom,

00:45:16.846 --> 00:45:18.375
was trying to convince him
to come out

00:45:18.575 --> 00:45:20.133
to the family place
at Hood Canal

00:45:20.333 --> 00:45:22.295
to meet Warren Buffett,
and he was resisting

00:45:22.495 --> 00:45:24.258
because he was
really busy with Microsoft.

00:45:24.458 --> 00:45:27.959
And finally he said, "Mom,
okay, I'll come for lunch."

00:45:28.159 --> 00:45:29.717
????

00:45:29.917 --> 00:45:31.959
Bill Gates:
So the two of us flew out there

00:45:32.159 --> 00:45:33.550
somewhat reluctantly,
'cause you know,

00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:36.300
buying and selling stocks...
which is how I thought of Warren...

00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:40.792
wasn't of particular interest to me
and didn't seem like value added.

00:45:40.992 --> 00:45:42.883
It turned out
that was completely wrong.

00:45:43.083 --> 00:45:46.316
We knew that day that
we'd be very close friends.

00:45:46.516 --> 00:45:49.750
In fact, we just couldn't
get enough of each other.

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:51.008
????

00:45:51.208 --> 00:45:52.759
Warren:
Shortly after I met Bill Gates,

00:45:52.959 --> 00:45:55.983
Bill's dad asked each of us to
write down on a piece of paper

00:45:56.183 --> 00:45:59.208
one word that would best describe
what had helped us the most.

00:45:59.408 --> 00:46:01.834
Bill and I, without any
collaboration at all,

00:46:02.034 --> 00:46:03.333
each wrote the word "focus."

00:46:03.533 --> 00:46:05.133
????

00:46:05.333 --> 00:46:08.733
Well, focus has always been a
strong part of my personality.

00:46:08.933 --> 00:46:12.133
If I get interested in something,
I get really interested.

00:46:12.333 --> 00:46:14.883
If I get interested in a new subject,
I want to read about it,

00:46:15.083 --> 00:46:18.500
I want to talk about it, and I want to
meet people that are involved in it.

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:22.050
Bill:
We both love to work hard.

00:46:22.250 --> 00:46:24.545
You know, neither of us
like frivolous things.

00:46:24.745 --> 00:46:28.126
You know he doesn't know
much about cooking,

00:46:28.326 --> 00:46:31.508
or art, or...
a huge range of things.

00:46:31.708 --> 00:46:36.000
I can't tell you the color of the
walls in my bedroom or my living room.

00:46:36.200 --> 00:46:37.300
We're on a satellite phone.

00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:40.208
I don't have a mind that relates
to the physical universe well.

00:46:40.408 --> 00:46:41.675
Man:
Warren checking the DOW.

00:46:41.875 --> 00:46:45.792
But the business universe I...
I think I understand reasonably well.

00:46:47.041 --> 00:46:50.625
Warren's ability to size
up people and businesses,

00:46:50.825 --> 00:46:52.717
it's a pretty magical thing.

00:46:52.917 --> 00:46:55.508
He is the best at that,
anybody we know.

00:46:55.708 --> 00:46:59.542
We... we should all try to be
20% as... as good at that.

00:47:04.208 --> 00:47:05.217
Warren:
I like to sit and think,

00:47:05.417 --> 00:47:07.717
and I spend
a lot of time doing that.

00:47:07.917 --> 00:47:10.542
And sometimes it's
pretty unproductive but...

00:47:10.742 --> 00:47:14.917
but I find it enjoyable
to think about...

00:47:15.117 --> 00:47:16.417
particularly about...
about business

00:47:16.617 --> 00:47:17.717
or investment problems.
They're easy.

00:47:17.917 --> 00:47:19.717
It's the human problems
that are the tough ones.

00:47:19.917 --> 00:47:22.358
Sometimes there aren't any good
answers with human problems.

00:47:22.558 --> 00:47:25.000
There's... there's almost always
a good answer with money.

00:47:32.041 --> 00:47:35.250
????

00:47:38.458 --> 00:47:40.583
Susie:
He was sort of a genius.

00:47:41.667 --> 00:47:44.879
I think sometimes
geniuses are,

00:47:45.079 --> 00:47:48.291
by default,
lonely and isolated.

00:47:51.708 --> 00:47:55.083
He was not
really well adjusted.

00:47:55.283 --> 00:47:57.717
He was just this funny...

00:47:57.917 --> 00:48:02.083
I mean,
humorous guy who maybe had a moat around him,

00:48:02.283 --> 00:48:06.834
because he was afraid
and he didn't know anyone

00:48:07.034 --> 00:48:09.250
that he wanted to let in.

00:48:11.667 --> 00:48:15.959
And to this day,
I mean, I don't know...

00:48:17.333 --> 00:48:19.091
Well, nobody
knows him like I do,

00:48:19.291 --> 00:48:22.959
and probably any wife
would say that, but...

00:48:23.159 --> 00:48:25.708
????

00:48:27.959 --> 00:48:30.425
Howard:
He's a loner in a sense.

00:48:30.625 --> 00:48:33.425
And it's difficult to connect
on an emotional level,

00:48:33.625 --> 00:48:38.667
because I think that that's not
his basic mode of operation.

00:48:40.333 --> 00:48:43.925
He was there... physically,

00:48:44.125 --> 00:48:47.917
but he was upstairs
reading all the time.

00:48:50.166 --> 00:48:53.717
I always told my mother
we have to talk in sound bytes.

00:48:53.917 --> 00:48:58.175
I learned that early on,
that if you start going into some long thing,

00:48:58.375 --> 00:49:01.500
unless you've explained to him ahead of
time that it's going to be a long thing

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:05.667
and you need him to hang in there,
you lose him.

00:49:05.867 --> 00:49:07.959
You lose him
to whatever giant thought

00:49:08.159 --> 00:49:09.508
he has in his head at the time

00:49:09.708 --> 00:49:12.583
that he was probably thinking
about before you came in

00:49:12.783 --> 00:49:14.500
and really wants
to get back to.

00:49:14.700 --> 00:49:17.375
????

00:49:18.834 --> 00:49:20.841
Peter:
He's not like the rest of us.

00:49:21.041 --> 00:49:24.333
I don't think my dad ever
took anybody for granted,

00:49:24.533 --> 00:49:26.800
but you are
a little bit blind, I think,

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:30.375
sometimes to what other people
might be doing behind the scenes,

00:49:30.575 --> 00:49:33.250
and my dad's gotten
a little bit of a pass.

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:35.634
????

00:49:35.834 --> 00:49:38.291
Susie:
Warren can't find the light switch,

00:49:38.491 --> 00:49:40.175
and it's probably my fault.

00:49:40.375 --> 00:49:44.041
One time, years ago
when the kids were little,

00:49:44.241 --> 00:49:46.050
I was feeling really sick.
I had the flu,

00:49:46.250 --> 00:49:48.091
so I lay down on the bed,
and I said to Warren,

00:49:48.291 --> 00:49:51.542
"Will you get me a pan?
Or something from the kitchen.

00:49:51.742 --> 00:49:54.592
I may not get to the bathroom.
I feel so sick."

00:49:54.792 --> 00:49:58.792
He said, "Okay."
So he trottles down to the kitchen,

00:49:58.992 --> 00:50:02.383
and I hear this bang,
bip, boom, bang!

00:50:02.583 --> 00:50:06.383
And he comes up,
and he brings me a colander.

00:50:06.583 --> 00:50:10.917
I looked at it, and I said, "Look,
honey, this has holes in it."

00:50:11.117 --> 00:50:13.979
"Oh, oh, okay."
So he ran down,

00:50:14.179 --> 00:50:16.841
all this banging
and everything.

00:50:17.041 --> 00:50:21.708
And he comes up and he puts the
colander on a cookie sheet.

00:50:26.417 --> 00:50:31.291
Physical proximity to Warren doesn't
always mean that he's there with you.

00:50:31.491 --> 00:50:34.050
????

00:50:34.250 --> 00:50:36.792
He's so cerebral, you see?

00:50:40.375 --> 00:50:42.750
That's why I learned
to have my own life.

00:50:42.950 --> 00:50:45.342
We were
two parallel lines and...

00:50:45.542 --> 00:50:49.875
but very connected when
he was open to connecting.

00:50:53.291 --> 00:50:55.458
Susie Jr.: I did make a joke at one point.
I said, you know,

00:50:55.658 --> 00:50:57.500
we could make
a tape of Mom yelling,

00:50:57.700 --> 00:50:59.342
"Bye, Warren,
I'll be back later!"

00:50:59.542 --> 00:51:03.959
And then have the door slam,
and he would just think she was here.

00:51:04.159 --> 00:51:06.625
I don't think he knew what she
was doing most of the time.

00:51:06.825 --> 00:51:09.258
????

00:51:09.458 --> 00:51:10.925
Once Howie and I
were both gone,

00:51:11.125 --> 00:51:15.208
as we've gotten older, she started
to see the writing on the wall here

00:51:15.408 --> 00:51:17.437
and just started
trying to figure out

00:51:17.637 --> 00:51:19.760
how she could
at least have some more,

00:51:19.960 --> 00:51:22.083
as she called it,
a room of her own.

00:51:22.283 --> 00:51:26.583
????

00:51:29.166 --> 00:51:31.091
Warren:
The worst mistakes involve

00:51:31.291 --> 00:51:34.667
not understanding other people
as well as you might.

00:51:44.750 --> 00:51:47.508
Well, she left Omaha in 1977,

00:51:47.708 --> 00:51:51.333
and there really isn't much
to say about that.

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:04.342
It was devastating for him,
and I came home,

00:52:04.542 --> 00:52:09.542
because I-I... I can't say
I was mad at her exactly,

00:52:09.742 --> 00:52:12.383
but I kept thinking,
"How can you leave him?

00:52:12.583 --> 00:52:17.175
He's so...
he can't function by himself."

00:52:17.375 --> 00:52:21.567
So my mother...
she'd asked a bunch of her friends

00:52:21.767 --> 00:52:25.959
to sort of look in on him,
and Astrid was one of them.

00:52:26.159 --> 00:52:28.375
Susie: So I called Astrid.
I said, "Astrid,

00:52:28.575 --> 00:52:30.792
"will you take Warren...
make him some soup?

00:52:30.992 --> 00:52:33.187
"Go over there
and look after him,

00:52:33.387 --> 00:52:35.383
because he's not
gonna make it."

00:52:35.583 --> 00:52:39.917
And it took him a while to figure it out,
but he figured it out.

00:52:40.117 --> 00:52:41.841
I said, "I'm not leaving you,

00:52:42.041 --> 00:52:45.667
because I'll be wherever you
want me when you want me."

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:49.634
Howard:
My mom moved to San Francisco,

00:52:49.834 --> 00:52:53.462
and I think one of the reasons it
was important for her to leave Omaha

00:52:53.662 --> 00:52:57.291
was because she just felt like she was
kinda trapped in this environment,

00:52:57.491 --> 00:52:59.467
that everybody knew
who she was,

00:52:59.667 --> 00:53:03.217
that she couldn't have
her own identity.

00:53:03.417 --> 00:53:05.883
Peter: He knew that there was
something she needed to do

00:53:06.083 --> 00:53:11.667
and that she really recognized
that the money gave us all and her

00:53:11.867 --> 00:53:15.542
a choice in a lot of ways that
a lot of people didn't have.

00:53:15.742 --> 00:53:19.217
Munger: There was a time
Warren was getting criticized.

00:53:19.417 --> 00:53:23.375
Here was this very, very rich man
who was getting richer every year,

00:53:23.575 --> 00:53:26.125
and really wasn't giving
a lot of money away,

00:53:26.325 --> 00:53:28.875
and there was terrific
criticism by some people,

00:53:29.075 --> 00:53:31.208
which Warren never said
anything about.

00:53:32.458 --> 00:53:34.425
Warren:
The biggest thing in making money is time.

00:53:34.625 --> 00:53:39.166
You don't have to be particularly smart,
you just have to be patient.

00:53:39.366 --> 00:53:41.091
Susie didn't want
to wait as much as I did,

00:53:41.291 --> 00:53:45.542
but she never quite appreciated
compounding like I did.

00:53:45.742 --> 00:53:48.250
Susie:
That is a disagreement we have.

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:50.675
I run a foundation now.

00:53:50.875 --> 00:53:54.000
I think we should be
giving more money away,

00:53:54.200 --> 00:53:57.000
but I understand
why we don't...

00:53:57.200 --> 00:53:59.717
because it's... business.

00:53:59.917 --> 00:54:04.500
To me the crux of it is,
that it wasn't the money itself.

00:54:04.700 --> 00:54:07.312
You can see that
in the way he lives.

00:54:07.512 --> 00:54:09.925
I mean, he doesn't buy
huge paintings

00:54:10.125 --> 00:54:12.425
or build big houses
or anything like that.

00:54:12.625 --> 00:54:17.500
It's all mental with him,
and the money is his scorecard.

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:19.008
????

00:54:19.208 --> 00:54:21.342
And he used to say to me,

00:54:21.542 --> 00:54:24.166
"Everybody can read
what I read.

00:54:24.366 --> 00:54:26.217
It's a level playing field."

00:54:26.417 --> 00:54:28.800
And he loves that,
because he's competitive.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:32.545
And he's sitting there
all by himself in his office,

00:54:32.745 --> 00:54:36.314
reading these things
that everybody else can read,

00:54:36.514 --> 00:54:40.083
but he loves the idea
that he's gonna win. Ha!

00:54:43.500 --> 00:54:45.333
Munger:
I'll tell you how you do it.

00:54:46.208 --> 00:54:48.041
Have you ever seen a juggler

00:54:48.241 --> 00:54:50.300
juggle 25 milk bottles?

00:54:50.500 --> 00:54:52.800
How did
he ever get to do that?

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:56.041
The answer is he started with one bottle,
then two, then three

00:54:56.241 --> 00:54:58.875
and just kept doing it,
and pretty soon he was at 25,

00:54:59.075 --> 00:55:00.966
and that's the way we did it.

00:55:01.166 --> 00:55:03.754
So, basically,
we started out with cash

00:55:03.954 --> 00:55:06.542
and ended up buying
a bunch of businesses,

00:55:06.742 --> 00:55:08.258
including insurance companies.

00:55:08.458 --> 00:55:13.125
Loomis: Insurance is, in itself,
a profitable business,

00:55:13.325 --> 00:55:15.592
but it has
the additional advantage

00:55:15.792 --> 00:55:18.962
of creating something
that's called "float."

00:55:19.162 --> 00:55:22.333
Float is the money
that hangs around Berkshire

00:55:22.533 --> 00:55:24.634
while a claim is waiting
to be paid.

00:55:24.834 --> 00:55:29.458
And Warren turned out
to have a extraordinary ability

00:55:29.658 --> 00:55:32.008
to use the money
thrown off by the float

00:55:32.208 --> 00:55:36.166
to buy companies that fed
the growth of Berkshire.

00:55:38.917 --> 00:55:42.291
Man: In 1983,
Mrs. B cashed in on her business

00:55:42.491 --> 00:55:45.383
by selling control
for $55 million

00:55:45.583 --> 00:55:48.250
to a company owned
by investor Warren Buffett.

00:55:48.450 --> 00:55:50.708
????

00:55:54.417 --> 00:55:58.500
Loomis:
Warren was quite an expert about newspapers.

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:00.375
He got interested
in the "Post,"

00:56:00.575 --> 00:56:01.592
because he recognized it

00:56:01.792 --> 00:56:04.917
as a greatly
undervalued company.

00:56:06.250 --> 00:56:07.717
Kay Graham:
He had to write me a letter.

00:56:07.917 --> 00:56:11.041
"Dear Ms. Graham,
I've just bought 5% of your company,

00:56:11.241 --> 00:56:12.592
"and I mean you no harm,

